{"title":"Reward-Weighted Regression Converges to a Global Optimum","domain":"RL","seeds":[{"problem":"EM-based Reward-Weighted Regression (RWR) is known to provide monotonic policy improvements under some conditions, but it lacked a clear, analyzable policy update in terms of value functions and precise conditions guaranteeing improvement without relying on potentially distorting nonlinear reward transformations.","method":"Derive a closed-form RWR policy update (no function approximation) expressed via value functions: define B(π) with π_{n+1}(a|s) = (Q^{π_n}(s,a)/V^{π_n}(s)) · π_n(a|s). Prove this induces monotonic improvement of both V^{π} and Q^{π} at every state-action (Theorem 4.1), with strict improvement whenever Var_{a∼π_n(·|s)}[Q^{π_n}(s,a)]>0. Show that nonlinear reward transformations can change the optimal policy (Appendix A), so restrict to linear shifts yielding strictly positive rewards to ground the update and analysis (Theorem 3.1)."},{"problem":"Whether and under what conditions RWR converges to an optimal policy remained open, especially in general compact (continuous or mixed) state/action spaces without function approximation.","method":"Establish global convergence of RWR to an optimal policy in compact spaces with strictly positive bounded rewards and an initial policy continuous and positive over actions. The proof shows V_n increases pointwise to V_L and Q_n→Q_L uniformly (via Q_L=W(V_L) and Dini’s theorem), and policy measures π_n(·|s) converge weakly relative to M(s)=argmax_a Q_L(s,a) using a quotient-topology/Portmanteau argument. It follows that (V_L,Q_L) are fixed points of the Bellman optimality operator and π_L is greedy w.r.t. Q_L, hence optimal (Theorem 5.1)."},{"problem":"RWR lacked established convergence rates, limiting understanding of its efficiency and practical behavior, particularly in finite MDPs.","method":"In the finite state/action setting, bound the probability mass that π_n assigns to suboptimal actions by constructing sets A_ε and B_ε and bounding policy ratios (Lemma 5.2), yielding R-linear convergence of values: ||V*−V_n||_∞ = O(α_m^n) with 0≤α_m<1 depending on λ_m = max_{s} max_{a∉M(s)} Q*(s,a)/V*(s) (Corollary 5.1). Provide examples demonstrating the linear rate is tight in finite MDPs and that in continuous action spaces the rate can be sub-linear Θ(1/n) (Appendix D)."}]}
